fields.name: Chicken and Vegetable Stir-Fry with Rice
fields.description: This Chicken and Vegetable Stir-Fry is a quick and nutritious meal perfect for bulking. Tender chicken breast is stir-fried with a colorful mix of vegetables and coated in a savory blend of soy and hoisin sauces. Served over a bed of fluffy rice, this dish provides a balanced combination of protein, fiber, and carbohydrates, making it ideal for a satisfying and energy-boosting lunch.
instructions: Heat 15 milliliters of olive oil in a large skillet or wok over medium-high heat.
Add the minced garlic and ginger to the skillet. Cook for about 1 minute, or until fragrant, stirring frequently to prevent burning.
Add the chicken pieces to the skillet. Cook for 5-7 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the chicken is browned and cooked through (internal temperature should reach 75C or 165F).
Add the mixed vegetables to the skillet with the chicken. Continue to stir-fry for an additional 3-5 minutes, or until the vegetables are tender-crisp.
Stir in 15 milliliters of soy sauce and 7.5 milliliters of hoisin sauce. Cook for another 2-3 minutes, ensuring that the chicken and vegetables are evenly coated with the sauce.
Taste and adjust seasoning with salt and pepper if needed.
Serve the chicken and vegetable stir-fry over 150 grams of cooked rice.

fields.name: Salmon Teriyaki with Rice
fields.description: This Salmon Teriyaki with Rice is a simple yet delicious high-protein meal perfect for bulking. The salmon is coated in a sweet and savory teriyaki glaze and baked to perfection. Served alongside rice and optionally paired with steamed asparagus or green beans, this dish is both nutritious and satisfying, making it a great choice for lunch.
instructions: Preheat the oven to 190C (375F). Line a baking sheet with parchment paper for easy cleanup.
In a small bowl, mix 30 milliliters of teriyaki sauce with 10 milliliters of honey until well combined.
Place the salmon fillet on the lined baking sheet. Brush the top of the salmon evenly with the teriyaki and honey mixture, making sure it's well coated.

Place the baking sheet in the preheated oven and bake the salmon for 15-20 minutes, or until the salmon is cooked through and flakes easily with a fork (internal temperature should reach 63C or 145F).
While the salmon is baking, steam 100 grams of asparagus or green beans until tender. This step is optional but adds extra nutrients to the meal.
Once the salmon is done, serve it over 150 grams of cooked white or brown rice.
Optionally, place the steamed vegetables on the side.
Garnish with sesame seeds for extra flavor and presentation.

fields.name: Special Cancer Egg
fields.description: This dish is special edition established from seasoned 1103's chef. The texture of the crispy egg blend with the hot sensation of sambal is a perfect combination to fulfill your feast.
instructions: In a medium bowl, crack the eggs and add seasoning with salt and pepper.
Whisk the mixture until the yolks and whites are fully combined and slightly frothy.
Place a frying pot over high heat.
Add the oil to the pot until approximately the egg can be covered perfectly with the oil.
Once the oil is hot (it should shimmer), pour the egg mixture into the pot slowly.
As you pour, create a gentle swirl in the oil to help the omelette get crispy.
Cook the omelette until the bottom is golden brown and crispy, about 2-3 minutes.
Carefully flip the omelette using a spatula and cook the other side until it�s also golden brown.
Once both sides are cooked, take the omelette out of the oil and let it drain on a paper towel to remove excess oil.
Serve the omelette over a bed of cooked rice.
Top with sambal for added flavor and spice.

fields.name: Bulk-Up Power Meal Kit
fields.description: The Bulk-Up Power Meal Kit is designed for individuals aiming to increase muscle mass while enjoying delicious, nutrient-dense meals. This meal kit includes two high-protein recipes: Chicken and Vegetable Stir-Fry with Rice and Salmon Teriyaki with Rice. Both dishes feature a balanced combination of lean protein, wholesome vegetables, and satisfying rice, ensuring you're fueled with the right nutrients to support muscle growth and recovery. Each meal is simple to prepare, making it perfect for those with busy lifestyles but still looking to meet their fitness goals.

fields.name: Garlic Head Each
fields.description:
Bulb made up of segments called cloves, covered by a papery shell. The most common varieties of garlic contain 10 cloves (or segments) with white skin. Other varieties have pink or purple skin and larger cloves. As a rule, the smaller the clove, the stronger the taste. 
It is a member of the allium family that also includes onions, chives, shallots, spring onions and leeks.

What to look for
Look for firm well-shaped cloves. Buy in small amounts and break off the cloves only when needed. Garlic dries out once detached. bulb of garlic has had its roots trimmed, one at a time. Garlic is never labelled since it sheds its skin if a label is applied to it.

Availability
All year.

Store
Keep in a cool dry place away from the sunlight. Avoid placing in plastic bags, or storing in the refrigerator or everything in the refrigerator will end up tasting of garlic. Avoid storing next to ginger as ginger dehydrates garlic.

How to prepare
Separate cloves from bulbs, remove papery skin unless roasting when skin can be left on. Cut bulbs in half crosswise and brush with oil to roast. To remove skin, press the clove under the flat side of a knife and the skin will come off easily. Chop the garlic very finely or crush it with the side of a knife. Alternatively, use a garlic crusher.

Ways to eat
Garlic can be eaten raw or cooked. Raw garlic produces a strong, pungent flavour while cooking gives a more mellow flavour. The longer garlic is cooked, the milder and sweeter the flavour. It's usually used in small amounts, 2-3 cloves to a dish. Garlic burns easily, so take care when frying or sauteing. It can be used in vegetable dishes, meats, soups, dips, stir fries, braises and stews. Add whole unpeeled cloves into a roasting pan with meat or vegetables. Cut a whole head in half horizontally and roast in a little olive oil. When cooked, serve as it is, or squeeze the roasted flesh out and serve on crostini or fresh bread.

Cooking Methods
Roast, braise, stew, stir fry.
